TI  - Resorbable 3D-Printed Osteosynthetic Plates for Rib Fracture Repair.
PG  - e2500409
LID - 10.1002/adhm.202500409 [doi]
AB  - Rib fractures are common among blunt chest trauma patients and are a hallmark of 
      severe thoracic injury with high morbidity and mortality rates. The standard 
      treatment of most rib fracture cases is limited to pain control and respiratory 
      support, with the surgical stabilization of rib fractures (SSRF) using titanium 
      plates reserved for severely injured patients. Although SSRF has been shown to 
      improve long-term patient outcomes, its expanded use has been limited by the 
      invasiveness of the procedure and a lack of safe and effective resorbable 
      fixation materials. While resorbable metal and polymeric plates have each been 
      used in the clinic, many failures have been reported and challenges remain to 
      control the mechanical properties of the plate during the degradation process. 
      The 3D printing of resorbable, fumarate-based copolyester-hydroxyapatite (HAp) 
      composite osteosynthetic plates for use in SSRF is presented, and assess their 
      efficacy in vivo in a rabbit rib fracture model. Compared to rigid titanium 
      fixation plates, ribs fixed with 3D printed composite plates elicit fracture 
      calluses with decreased inflammatory response, enhanced osseointegration, and 
      bone morphometry at 2- and 4-weeks post-fracture comparable to clinically used 
      titanium plates.
