PMID- 38225829
OWN - NLM
STAT- PubMed-not-MEDLINE
LR  - 20240314
IS  - 2765-1606 (Print)
IS  - 2765-1614 (Electronic)
IS  - 2765-1606 (Linking)
VI  - 57
IP  - 2
DP  - 2024 Mar 5
TI  - Surgical Rib Fracture Fixation: Early Operative Intervention Improves Outcomes.
PG  - 120-125
LID - 10.5090/jcs.23.095 [doi]
AB  - BACKGROUND: This study aimed to assess the outcomes of patients with complex rib 
      fractures undergoing operative or nonoperative management at our major trauma 
      center. METHODS: A retrospective review of all patients who were considered for 
      surgical stabilization of rib fractures (SSRF) at a single major trauma center 
      from May 2016 to September 2022 was performed. RESULTS: In total, 352 patients 
      with complex rib fractures were identified. Thirty-seven patients (11%) fulfilled 
      the criteria for surgical management and underwent SSRF. The SSRF group had a 
      significantly higher proportion of patients with flail chest (32 [86%] vs. 94 
      [27%], p<0.001) or Injury Severity Score (ISS) >15 (37 [100%] vs. 129 [41%], 
      p<0.001). No significant differences were seen between groups for 1-year 
      mortality. Patients who underwent SSRF within 72 hours were 6 times less likely 
      to develop pneumonia than those in whom SSRF was delayed for over 72 hours (2 
      [18%] vs. 15 [58%]; odds ratio, 0.163; 95% confidence interval, 0.029-0.909; 
      p=0.036). Prompt SSRF showed non-significant associations with shorter intensive 
      care unit length of stay (6 days vs. 10 days, p=0.140) and duration of mechanical 
      ventilation (5 days vs. 8 days, p=0.177). SSRF was associated with a longer 
      hospital length of stay compared to nonoperative patients with flail chest and/or 
      ISS >15 (19 days vs. 13 days, p=0.012), whilst SSRF within 72 hours was not. 
      CONCLUSION: Surgical fixation of complex rib fractures improves outcomes in 
      selected patient groups. Delayed surgical fixation was associated with increased 
      rates of pneumonia and a longer hospital length of stay.
FAU - Dixon, James
