TI  - Open Reduction and Internal Fixation of a Chronic Precordial Flail Chest Segment: 
      A Case Report.
LID - 10.2106/JBJS.CC.22.00714 [doi]
AB  - CASE: We report on a 35-year-old man presenting with disabling pain secondary to 
      multiple rib nonunions and a costochondral dislocation 5 months after sustaining 
      a chest wall crush injury. He underwent surgical reconstruction of the chest and 
      was followed for 2 years. Surgical exposure to the heart was necessary during 
      open reduction of the flail segment, followed by costochondral joint fixation 
      with plates and screws. Although he was a workers' compensation patient, he 
      returned to full gainful employment. CONCLUSION: Open reduction and internal 
      fixation of a symptomatic, chronically displaced, precordial, flail segment can 
      relieve pain and promote return to baseline function.
